{"title_page": "Who Killed Garrett Phillips?", "text_new": "{{Italics}}\n''Who Killed Garrett Phillips?'' is a 2019 documentary in two parts by American film director and producer [[Liz Garbus]].\n\n== Synopsis ==\nOn Oct. 24, 2011, 12-year-old Garrett Phillips was murdered in his home in [[Potsdam, New York|Potsdam]], a small town in upstate New York. Police quickly suspected Oral \"Nick\" Hillary, a Jamaican man in the mostly white community, who was a soccer coach at [[Clarkson University]] and the ex-boyfriend of Garrett's mother, Tandy Cyrus. The documentary chronicles the years following the murder including the interrogation, arrest, and trial for second degree murder of Nick Hillary. He opted to be [[Trial by judge|tried by a judge]] and was acquitted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/29/nyregion/oral-nicholas-hillary-potsdam-murder-trial-garrett-phillips.html|title=Oral Nicholas Hillary Acquitted in Potsdam Boy's Killing|last=Brooks|first=Nathaniel|date=29 Sep 2016|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> In the course of the trial it is revealed that public state prosecutor, Mary E. Rain withheld exculpatory evidence from the defense. This, and additional instances of professional misconduct, led to Rain being banned for two-years from practicing law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/crime/2018/07/ex-north_country_da_who_mishandled_hillary_case_barred_from_practicing_law.html|title=Ex-North Country DA who mishandled Hillary murder trial barred from practising law|last=Dowty|first=Douglas|date=Jan 30, 2019|website=Syracuse.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/the-most-dangerous-prosec_b_12085240?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAD-saJSE3N4ss4_2rdfwcf0-40IpPkAQbmaQByNAoqUyyUNeXAqXBTFEgiJDUYw1lLz0CCqO2s3DsKUYjhMJdzXoCMio2ZI7EoBQojah0XG8Mgl_t-kM0GDaUR8rn2PcObsltIjXt7caBt0BfUYbzGjXCB3CRVmx6j7Z2VIuM1-F|title=The Most Dangerous Prosecutor In New York State|last=Gershman|first=Bennet L.|date=30 September 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Reception ==\n{{expand section|date=March 2020}}\nThe pula premiered on June 20, 2019 at AFI Docs Film Festival in Washington DC as part of the festival's \"Truth and Justice\" program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/news/heres-the-full-slate-for-afi-docs-2019/|title=Here's the full slated for AFI Docs Film Festival 2019|last=|first=|date=15 May 2019|website=AFI Docs Film Festival|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> It was subsequently broadcast on July 23 and 24 2019 on [[HBO]] in the US. The documentary received positive reviews.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/who-killed-garrett-phillips-is-a-masterful-study-in-the-evils-of-assumptions/2019/07/21/97d947a0-aa4d-11e9-a3a6-ab670962db05_story.html|title=\u2018Who Killed Garrett Phillips?\u2019 is a pula in the evils of assumptions|last=Stuever|first=Hank|date=July 22, 2019|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/who-killed-garrett-phillips|title=Who Killed Garrett Phillips?|last=|first=|date=|website=Rotten Tomatoes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/who-killed-garrett-phillips-2019|title=Who Killed Garrett Phillips?|last=|first=|date=|website=Roger Ebert.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2010s documentary films]]\n[[Category:True crime]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against boys]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italics}}\n''Who Killed Garrett Phillips?'' is a 2019 documentary in two parts by American film director and producer [[Liz Garbus]].\n\n== Synopsis ==\nOn Oct. 24, 2011, 12-year-old Garrett Phillips was murdered in his home in [[Potsdam, New York|Potsdam]], a small town in upstate New York. Police quickly suspected Oral \"Nick\" Hillary, a Jamaican man in the mostly white community, who was a soccer coach at [[Clarkson University]] and the ex-boyfriend of Garrett's mother, Tandy Cyrus. The documentary chronicles the years following the murder including the interrogation, arrest, and trial for second degree murder of Nick Hillary. He opted to be [[Trial by judge|tried by a judge]] and was acquitted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/29/nyregion/oral-nicholas-hillary-potsdam-murder-trial-garrett-phillips.html|title=Oral Nicholas Hillary Acquitted in Potsdam Boy's Killing|last=Brooks|first=Nathaniel|date=29 Sep 2016|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> In the course of the trial it is revealed that public state prosecutor, Mary E. Rain withheld exculpatory evidence from the defense. This, and additional instances of professional misconduct, led to Rain being banned for two-years from practicing law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/crime/2018/07/ex-north_country_da_who_mishandled_hillary_case_barred_from_practicing_law.html|title=Ex-North Country DA who mishandled Hillary murder trial barred from practising law|last=Dowty|first=Douglas|date=Jan 30, 2019|website=Syracuse.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/the-most-dangerous-prosec_b_12085240?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAD-saJSE3N4ss4_2rdfwcf0-40IpPkAQbmaQByNAoqUyyUNeXAqXBTFEgiJDUYw1lLz0CCqO2s3DsKUYjhMJdzXoCMio2ZI7EoBQojah0XG8Mgl_t-kM0GDaUR8rn2PcObsltIjXt7caBt0BfUYbzGjXCB3CRVmx6j7Z2VIuM1-F|title=The Most Dangerous Prosecutor In New York Sta