{"title_page": "Rudratej Singh", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian business executive}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rudratej Singh\n| image              = Rudratej Singh during an auto event.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = 22 June 1973\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{death date and given age|2020|4|20|46|df=y}}\n| death_place        = \n| resting_place      = \n| nationality        = Indian\n| citizenship        = Indian\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Career in [[Royal Enfield (India)|Royal Enfield Motors]] and [[Unilever]]\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Air Force Bal Bharati School]]<br>[[Delhi University]]<br>[[IMT Ghaziabad]]\n| employer           = [[BMW India]]\n| occupation         = [[CEO]], [[President (corporate title)|President]]\n| years_active       = \n| home_town          = \n| networth           = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Rudratej Singh''' (22 June 1973 \u2013 20 April 2020) was an [[India/People|Indian]] business executive. He was the first Indian \nPresident & CEO of [[BMW India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/sectors/auto/former-royal-enfield-chief-rudratej-singh-to-now-lead-bmw-india/story/357547.html|title=Former Royal Enfield chief Rudratej Singh to now lead BMW India|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/auto-news/rudratej-singh-former-royal-enfield-president-to-head-bmw-india-1560945636948.html|title=Rudratej Singh, former Royal Enfield boss, to head BMW India|last=Panday|first=Amit|date=2019-06-19|website=Livemint.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> Singh was known for his former positions as Global President of [[Royal Enfield (India)|Royal Enfield Motors Limited]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://auto.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/industry/bmw-appoints-ex-royal-enfield-chief-rudratej-singh-appointed-as-president-ceo-of-india-operations/69859474|title=Ex-Royal Enfield sales head Rudratej Singh appointed as President & CEO of BMW Group India - ET Auto|website=[[The Economic Times]]|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> and Vice President of [[Unilever]] in Singapore.<ref name=\":0\" /> He passed away due to Cardiac Arrest at the age of 46.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSingh grew up in New Delhi. He completed his schooling from [[Air Force Bal Bharati School]], batch of 1990. He graduated in Commerce from [[Delhi University]] in 1993 and then moved on to the [[IMT Ghaziabad]] to study MBA in Marketing and Finance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inshorts.com/en/news/rudratej-singh-former-royal-enfield-president-to-head-bmw-india-1561001423685|title=Rudratej Singh, former Royal Enfield President, to head BMW India|website=Inshorts - Stay Informed|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> In 2014, he undertook Advanced Management Program from [[Harvard Business School]].\n\n==Career==\nSingh started his career in 1996 as a Senior Product Manager at the [[Dabur|Dabur India Limited]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.autoactu.com/rudratej-singh-nomme-president-directeur-general-de-bmw-group-inde.shtml|title=autoactu.com - l'information automobile professionnelle|website=www.autoactu.com|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> He then joined as Area Sales Manager in [[Hindustan Unilever]] in August 1998. In 2000, he was then promoted to Sr Brand Manager, within Hindustan Unilever,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/magazine/event/business-today-honda-pro-am-of-champions-event/story/12884.html|title=Happy Valley- Business News|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> where he was one of the key people to create the Brooke Bond master brand. Since then, he has held senior positions in the Hindustan Unilever Ltd and Unilever PLC across various developed and developing markets globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/company-officers/EICH.NSf|title=${Instrument_CompanyName} ${Instrument_Ric} People {{!}} Reuters.com|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|website=U.S.|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/rudratej-singh-appointed-bmw-group-india-president-and-chief-executive-119061901266_1.html|title=Rudratej Singh appointed BMW Group India President and Chief Executive|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|date=2019-06-19|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>\n\nIn Jan 2015, he moved from Unilever and joined Eicher Motors Limited (EML) as their President of flagship motorcycle business, Royal Enfield and member of the Management Team of [[Eicher Motors|Eicher Motors Limited]] (EML).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://overdrive.in/news-cars-auto/rudratej-singh-quits-royal-enfield-with-immediate-effect/|title=Rudratej Singh quits Royal Enfield with immediate effect|website=Overdrive|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>  In 2017, Singh was promoted to the Global President of Royal Enfield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/bmw-group-names-rudratej-singh-as-president-and-ceo-for-india-4116681.html|title=BMW Group names Rudratej Singh as president and CEO for India|website=Moneycontrol|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/royal-enfield-appoints-rudratej-singh-as-president/articleshow/45929893.cms|title=Royal Enfield appoints Rudratej Singh as President|date=2015-01-19|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/auto/auto-news/story/royal-enfield-sets-up-direct-sales-subsidiary-in-the-us-plans-to-open-retail-stores-288812-2015-08-18|title=Royal Enfield sets up direct sales subsidiary in the US; plans to open retail stores|last=DelhiAugust 18|first=Press Trust of India New|last2=August 18|first2=2015UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01|last3=Ist|first3=2015 10:19}}</ref> During his four year tenure, he helped Royal Enfield become one of the most profitable auto companies in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/royal-enfields-rudratej-singh-quits/article25941078.ece|title=Rudratej Singh quits Royal Enfield|last=PTI|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/article/super-50-companies-2015/eicher-motors-its-all-in-the-drive/40705/1|title=Eicher Motors: It's all in the drive|website=Forbes India|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> His efforts also helped grow the company\u2019s market share in India from 3.3%, in 2014, to 6.9%, in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eicher.in/uploads/1518004619_press-release-eicher-motors-results-Q3-2017-18.pdf|title=Eicher Motors Limited registers record performance in the quarter ended December 31st, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/markets/eicher-motors-stock-jumps-on-plan-to-increase-royal-enfield-capacity|title=Eicher Motors' Stock Jumps On Plan To Increase Royal Enfield Capacity|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Singh quit Royal Enfield after serving for four years<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/two-wheelers/royal-enfield-president-rudratej-singh-quits-lalit-malik-to-take-charge/articleshow/67438710.cms|title=Royal Enfield President Rudratej Singh quits, Lalit Malik to take charge|date=2019-01-08|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocarpro.in/News/royal-enfield\u2019s-president-rudratej-singh-quits-41770|title=Royal Enfield's president Rudratej Singh quits|website=Autocarpro.in|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> and joined BMW India as its President and Chief Executive Officer (CEO) with his term starting from August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zeebiz.com/automobile/news-bmw-group-india-gets-new-ceo-who-is-rudratej-rudy-singh-profile-102807|title=BMW Group India gets new CEO - Who is Rudratej 'Rudy' Singh? Profile|date=2019-06-19|website=Zee Business|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afaqs.com/people-spotting/463_Former-Enfield-hand-Rudratej-Singh-joins-BMW-India-as-president-and-CEO|title=Former Enfield hand Rudratej Singh joins BMW India as president and CEO|date=2019-06-23|website=www.afaqs.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auto.ndtv.com/news/rudratej-singh-appointed-president-and-ceo-of-bmw-group-india-2055903|title=Rudratej Singh Appointed President And CEO Of BMW Group India - NDTV CarAndBike|website=CarAndBike|language=English|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> He died on 20 April 2020 at the age of 46 from cardiac arrest.<ref>[http://everythingexperiential.businessworld.in/article/Rudratej-Singh-President-CEO-of-BMW-Group-India-is-no-more/20-04-2020-189621/ Rudratej Singh, President & CEO of BMW Group India is no more]</ref>\n\n== Other activities ==\nSingh has represented India as an amateur golfer and has won 18 titles globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://overdrive.in/news-cars-auto/rudratej-singh-appointed-as-new-president-of-royal-enfield/|title=Rudratej Singh appointed as new president of Royal Enfield|website=Overdrive|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> He was also a board member of the Women\u2019s Golf Association of India (WGAI),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/golfdigestindia/docs/gd_02_2018/34|title=Golf Digest India - February 2018|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> and helped run a charity for underprivileged (girl) children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cmocouncil.org/profiles/7486|title=Members - CMO Council\u2122|website=www.cmocouncil.org|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> He spoke regularly at various business and brand forums across the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocarindia.com/bike-news/rudratej-singh-is-royal-enfield8217s-new-president-392882|title=Rudratej Singh is Royal Enfield's new President|website=Autocar India|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 2012 - Marketer of the Year by the World CMO Council - Asia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiainfoline.com/article/news-top-story/royal-enfield-appoints-rudratej-singh-as-president-115011900010_1.html|title=Royal Enfield appoints Rudratej Singh as President|website=www.indiainfoline.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n*2007 - Hindustan Unilever Directors Award<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/hul-allcargo-top-honchos-win-the-last-leg-of-et-golf/articleshow/5635162.cms?from=mdr|title=HUL, Allcargo top honchos win the last leg of ET golf|date=2010-03-03|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Rudratej}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:BMW people]]\n[[Category:Institute of Management Technology, Ghaziabad alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School Advanced Management Program attendees]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian business executive}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rudratej Singh\n| image              = Rudratej Singh during an auto event.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = 1973 or 1974\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{death date and given age|2020|4|20|46|df=y}}\n| death_place        = \n| resting_place      = \n| nationality        = Indian\n| citizenship        = Indian\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Career in [[Royal Enfield (India)|Royal Enfield Motors]] and [[Unilever]]\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Air Force Bal Bharati School]]<br>[[Delhi University]]<br>[[IMT Ghaziabad]]\n| employer           = [[BMW India]]\n| occupation         = [[CEO]], [[President (corporate title)|President]]\n| years_active       = \n| home_town          = \n| networth           = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Rudratej Singh''' (1973 or 1974 \u2013 20 April 2020) was an [[India/People|Indian]] business executive. He was the first Indian \nPresident & CEO of [[BMW India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/sectors/auto/former-royal-enfield-chief-rudratej-singh-to-now-lead-bmw-india/story/357547.html|title=Former Royal Enfield chief Rudratej Singh to now lead BMW India|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/auto-news/rudratej-singh-former-royal-enfield-president-to-head-bmw-india-1560945636948.html|title=Rudratej Singh, former Royal Enfield boss, to head BMW India|last=Panday|first=Amit|date=2019-06-19|website=Livemint.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> Singh was known for his former positions as Global President of [[Royal Enfield (India)|Royal Enfield Motors Limited]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://auto.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/industry/bmw-appoints-ex-royal-enfield-chief-rudratej-singh-appointed-as-president-ceo-of-india-operations/69859474|title=Ex-Royal Enfield sales head Rudratej Singh appointed as President & CEO of BMW Group India - ET Auto|website=[[The Economic Times]]|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> and Vice President of [[Unilever]] in Singapore.<ref name=\":0\" /> He passed away due to Cardiac Arrest at the age of 46.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSingh grew up in New Delhi. He completed his schooling from [[Air Force Bal Bharati School]], batch of 1990. He graduated in Commerce from [[Delhi University]] in 1993 and then moved on to the [[IMT Ghaziabad]] to study MBA in Marketing and Finance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inshorts.com/en/news/rudratej-singh-former-royal-enfield-president-to-head-bmw-india-1561001423685|title=Rudratej Singh, former Royal Enfield President, to head BMW India|website=Inshorts - Stay Informed|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> In 2014, he undertook Advanced Management Program from [[Harvard Business School]].\n\n==Career==\nSingh started his career in 1996 as a Senior Product Manager at the [[Dabur|Dabur India Limited]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.autoactu.com/rudratej-singh-nomme-president-directeur-general-de-bmw-group-inde.shtml|title=autoactu.com - l'information automobile professionnelle|website=www.autoactu.com|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> He then joined as Area Sales Manager in [[Hindustan Unilever]] in August 1998. In 2000, he was then promoted to Sr Brand Manager, within Hindustan Unilever,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/magazine/event/business-today-honda-pro-am-of-champions-event/story/12884.html|title=Happy Valley- Business News|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> where he was one of the key people to create the Brooke Bond master brand. Since then, he has held senior positions in the Hindustan Unilever Ltd and Unilever PLC across various developed and developing markets globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/company-officers/EICH.NSf|title=${Instrument_CompanyName} ${Instrument_Ric} People {{!}} Reuters.com|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|website=U.S.|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/rudratej-singh-appointed-bmw-group-india-president-and-chief-executive-119061901266_1.html|title=Rudratej Singh appointed BMW Group India President and Chief Executive|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|date=2019-06-19|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>\n\nIn Jan 2015, he moved from Unilever and joined Eicher Motors Limited (EML) as their President of flagship motorcycle business, Royal Enfield and member of the Management Team of [[Eicher Motors|Eicher Motors Limited]] (EML).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://overdrive.in/news-cars-auto/rudratej-singh-quits-royal-enfield-with-immediate-effect/|title=Rudratej Singh quits Royal Enfield with immediate effect|website=Overdrive|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>  In 2017, Singh was promoted to the Global President of Royal Enfield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/bmw-group-names-rudratej-singh-as-president-and-ceo-for-india-4116681.html|title=BMW Group names Rudratej Singh as president and CEO for India|website=Moneycontrol|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/royal-enfield-appoints-rudratej-singh-as-president/articleshow/45929893.cms|title=Royal Enfield appoints Rudratej Singh as President|date=2015-01-19|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/auto/auto-news/story/royal-enfield-sets-up-direct-sales-subsidiary-in-the-us-plans-to-open-retail-stores-288812-2015-08-18|title=Royal Enfield sets up direct sales subsidiary in the US; plans to open retail stores|last=DelhiAugust 18|first=Press Trust of India New|last2=August 18|first2=2015UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01|last3=Ist|first3=2015 10:19}}</ref> During his four year tenure, he helped Royal Enfield become one of the most profitable auto companies in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/royal-enfields-rudratej-singh-quits/article25941078.ece|title=Rudratej Singh quits Royal Enfield|last=PTI|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/article/super-50-companies-2015/eicher-motors-its-all-in-the-drive/40705/1|title=Eicher Motors: It's all in the drive|website=Forbes India|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> His efforts also helped grow the company\u2019s market share in India from 3.3%, in 2014, to 6.9%, in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eicher.in/uploads/1518004619_press-release-eicher-motors-results-Q3-2017-18.pdf|title=Eicher Motors Limited registers record performance in the quarter ended December 31st, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/markets/eicher-motors-stock-jumps-on-plan-to-increase-royal-enfield-capacity|title=Eicher Motors' Stock Jumps On Plan To Increase Royal Enfield Capacity|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Singh quit Royal Enfield after serving for four years<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/two-wheelers/royal-enfield-president-rudratej-singh-quits-lalit-malik-to-take-charge/articleshow/67438710.cms|title=Royal Enfield President Rudratej Singh quits, Lalit Malik to take charge|date=2019-01-08|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocarpro.in/News/royal-enfield\u2019s-president-rudratej-singh-quits-41770|title=Royal Enfield's president Rudratej Singh quits|website=Autocarpro.in|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> and joined BMW India as its President and Chief Executive Officer (CEO) with his term starting from August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zeebiz.com/automobile/news-bmw-group-india-gets-new-ceo-who-is-rudratej-rudy-singh-profile-102807|title=BMW Group India gets new CEO - Who is Rudratej 'Rudy' Singh? Profile|date=2019-06-19|website=Zee Business|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afaqs.com/people-spotting/463_Former-Enfield-hand-Rudratej-Singh-joins-BMW-India-as-president-and-CEO|title=Former Enfield hand Rudratej Singh joins BMW India as president and CEO|date=2019-06-23|website=www.afaqs.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auto.ndtv.com/news/rudratej-singh-appointed-president-and-ceo-of-bmw-group-india-2055903|title=Rudratej Singh Appointed President And CEO Of BMW Group India - NDTV CarAndBike|website=CarAndBike|language=English|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> He died on 20 April 2020 at the age of 46 from cardiac arrest.<ref>[http://everythingexperiential.businessworld.in/article/Rudratej-Singh-President-CEO-of-BMW-Group-India-is-no-more/20-04-2020-189621/ Rudratej Singh, President & CEO of BMW Group India is no more]</ref>\n\n== Other activities ==\nSingh has represented India as an amateur golfer and has won 18 titles globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://overdrive.in/news-cars-auto/rudratej-singh-appointed-as-new-president-of-royal-enfield/|title=Rudratej Singh appointed as new president of Royal Enfield|website=Overdrive|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> He was also a board member of the Women\u2019s Golf Association of India (WGAI),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/golfdigestindia/docs/gd_02_2018/34|title=Golf Digest India - February 2018|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> and helped run a charity for underprivileged (girl) children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cmocouncil.org/profiles/7486|title=Members - CMO Council\u2122|website=www.cmocouncil.org|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> He spoke regularly at various business and brand forums across the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocarindia.com/bike-news/rudratej-singh-is-royal-enfield8217s-new-president-392882|title=Rudratej Singh is Royal Enfield's new President|website=Autocar India|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 2012 - Marketer of the Year by the World CMO Council - Asia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiainfoline.com/article/news-top-story/royal-enfield-appoints-rudratej-singh-as-president-115011900010_1.html|title=Royal Enfield appoints Rudratej Singh as President|website=www.indiainfoline.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n*2007 - Hindustan Unilever Directors Award<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/hul-allcargo-top-honchos-win-the-last-leg-of-et-golf/articleshow/5635162.cms?from=mdr|title=HUL, Allcargo top honchos win the last leg of ET golf|date=2010-03-03|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Rudratej}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:BMW people]]\n[[Category:Institute of Management Technology, Ghaziabad alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School Advanced Management Program attendees]]\n", "name_user": "150.242.254.165", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudratej_Singh"}
{"title_page": "Ch'\u014fphae Sin\u014f", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{infobox Chinese\n|pic=File:Syoukaisingo genkanpon.jpg\n|hangul=\ucca9\ud574\uc2e0\uc5b4\n|hanja=\u6377\u89e3\u65b0\u8a9e\n|mr=Ch'\u014fphae Sin\u014f\n|rr=Cheopae sineo\n<!-- Yale: Chephay sine -->\n|kanji=\u6377\u89e3\u65b0\u8a9e\n|hiragana=\u3057\u3087\u3046\u304b\u3044\u3057\u3093\u3054\n|romaji=Sh\u014dkai Shingo\n|kunrei=Syoukaisingo\n}}\n'''''Ch'\u014fphae Sin\u014f''''' or '''''Sh\u014dkai Shingo''''' ('Rapid Understanding of a New Language') is a Korean textbook of colloquial [[Japanese language|Japanese]], written in 1618 by Kang Wusen and published posthumously in 1676.\nIt is a source for [[Late Middle Japanese]].<ref>{{citation\n  | surname = Martin | given = Samuel Elmo | author-link = Samuel Martin (linguist)\n  | title = The Japanese Language through Time\n  | location = New Haven and London | publisher = Yale University Press | year = 1987\n  | isbn = 978-0-300-03729-6\n  | page = 22\n  | postscript = .\n  }}</ref><ref>{{citation\n  | surname1 = Irwin | given1 = Mark | surname2 = Narrog | given2 = Heiko\n  | chapter = Late Middle Japanese\n  | pages = 246\u2013226\n  | title = The Languages of Japan and Korea\n  | editor-first = Nicolas | editor-last = Tranter\n  | publisher = Routledge | year = 2012\n  | isbn = 978-0-415-46287-7\n  | postscript = .\n  }} p. 246.</ref>\n\nKang was taken to Japan as a captive at the age of 12 during the [[Japanese invasions of Korea (1592\u20131598)|Japanese invasion of Korea in 1592]], and remained there for 10 years.\nAfter his return to Korea, he created a series of instructional materials on the Japanese language in the form of conversations involving Koreans travelling to Japan for business or diplomacy.\nThe Japanese text is written in large [[hiragana]], with a phonetic transcription in [[Hangul]] on the right and the Korean meaning, also in Hangul, on the left.<ref>{{citation\n  | title = Cheopae sineo (\u6377\u89e3\u65b0\u8a9e)\n  | publisher = National Hangeul Museum\n  | url = https://www.hangeul.go.kr/lang/en/museumCollection/museumCollectionView.do?pageIndex=3&collection_id=2&lang=en&seq=340&searchWordGubun=title&outResultCnt=8\n  | access-date = 21 April 2020\n  | postscript = .\n  }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons category-inline|\u6377\u89e3\u65b0\u8a9e|''Ch'\u014fphae Sin\u014f''}}\n* [http://waks.aks.ac.kr/rsh/dir/rview.aspx?rshID=AKS-2012-EBZ-2101&dataID=8359@AKS-2012-EBZ-2101_DES \ucca9\ud574\uc2e0\uc5b4(\u6377\u89e3\u65b0\u8a9e)] \u2013 description at the [[Academy of Korean Studies]]\n* [http://archives.hangeul.go.kr/scholarship/archives?searchEnable=1&keyword=%EC%B2%A9%ED%95%B4%EC%8B%A0%EC%96%B4&sorting=regDt&pm=by20 scanned volumes] at the Digital Hangeul Museum\n\n[[Category:Joseon Dynasty works]]\n[[Category:Late Middle Japanese texts]]\n[[Category:17th-century books]]\n\n{{Japonic-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{infobox Chinese\n|pic=File:Syoukaisingo genkanpon.jpg\n|hangul=\ucca9\ud574\uc2e0\uc5b4\n|hanja=\u6377\u89e3\u65b0\u8a9e\n|mr=Ch'\u014fphae Sin\u014f\n|rr=Cheopae sineo\n<!-- Yale: Chephay sine -->\n|kanji=\u6377\u89e3\u65b0\u8a9e\n|hiragana=\u3057\u3087\u3046\u304b\u3044\u3057\u3093\u3054\n|romaji=Sh\u014dkai Shingo\n|kunrei=Syoukaisingo\n}}\n'''''Ch'\u014fphae Sin\u014f''''' or '''''Sh\u014dkai Shingo''''' ('Rapid Understanding of a New Language') is a Korean textbook of colloquial [[Japanese language|Japanese]], written in 1618 by Kang Wusen and published posthumously in 1676.\nIt is a source for [[Late Middle Japanese]].<ref>{{citation\n  | surname = Martin | given = Samuel Elmo | author-link = Samuel Martin (linguist)\n  | title = The Japanese Language through Time\n  | location = New Haven and London | publisher = Yale University Press | year = 1987\n  | isbn = 978-0-300-03729-6\n  | page = 22\n  | postscript = .\n  }}</ref><ref>{{citation\n  | surname1 = Irwin | given1 = Mark | surname2 = Narrog | given2 = Heiko\n  | chapter = Late Middle Japanese\n  | pages = 246\u2013226\n  | title = The Languages of Japan and Korea\n  | editor-first = Nicolas | editor-last = Tranter\n  | publisher = Routledge | year = 2012\n  | isbn = 978-0-415-46287-7\n  | postscript = .\n  }} p. 246.</ref>\n\nKang was taken to Japan as a captive at the age of 12 during the [[Japanese invasions of Korea (1592\u20131598)|Japanese invasion of Korea in 1592]], and remained there for 10 years.\nAfter his return to Korea, he created a series of instructional materials on the Japanese language in the form of conversations involving Koreans travelling to Japan for business or diplomacy.\nThe Japanese text is written in large [[hiragana]], with a phonetic transcription in [[Hangul]] on the right and the Korean meaning, also in Hangul, on the left.<ref>{{citation\n  | title = Cheopae sineo (\u6377\u89e3\u65b0\u8a9e)\n  | publisher = Narional Hangeul Museum\n  | url = https://www.hangeul.go.kr/lang/en/museumCollection/museumCollectionView.do?pageIndex=3&collection_id=2&lang=en&seq=340&searchWordGubun=title&outResultCnt=8\n  | access-date = 21 April 2020\n  | postscript = .\n  }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons category-inline|\u6377\u89e3\u65b0\u8a9e|''Ch'\u014fphae Sin\u014f''}}\n* [http://waks.aks.ac.kr/rsh/dir/rview.aspx?rshID=AKS-2012-EBZ-2101&dataID=8359@AKS-2012-EBZ-2101_DES \ucca9\ud574\uc2e0\uc5b4(\u6377\u89e3\u65b0\u8a9e)] \u2013 description at the [[Academy of Korean Studies]]\n* [http://archives.hangeul.go.kr/scholarship/archives?searchEnable=1&keyword=%EC%B2%A9%ED%95%B4%EC%8B%A0%EC%96%B4&sorting=regDt&pm=by20 scanned volumes] at the Digital Hangeul Museum\n\n[[Category:Joseon Dynasty works]]\n[[Category:Late Middle Japanese texts]]\n[[Category:17th-century books]]\n\n{{Japonic-lang-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kanguole", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ch%27%C5%8Fphae_Sin%C5%8F"}
{"title_page": "Heinrich von Gossler", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n[[File:Heinrich von Go\u00dfler.JPG|thumb|Heinrich von Go\u00dfler]]\n'''Heinrich Wilhelm Martin von Go\u00dfler''' (29 September 1841, in [[Wei\u00dfenfels]], [[Province of Saxony]] &ndash; 10 January 1927, in [[Wilmersdorf|Berlin-Wilmersdorf]]) was a [[Prussia]]n [[General of the Infantry]] and [[Prussian Minister of War|Minister of War]]. He was a Knight of Justice (''Rechtsritter'') of the [[Order of Saint John (Bailiwick of Brandenburg)|Order of Saint John]].\n\n==Family==\nHe was descended from a family that probably originated from [[Lipov\u00e1 (Cheb District)|Gosel]] in the [[Egerland]] and emigrated to G\u00fcrth (now in [[Bad Brambach]]) before 1630. He was the son of Karl Gustav von Go\u00dfler (1810\u20131885), the ''Kanzler'' (in this case, provincial justice minister) of the province [[East Prussia]], legal advisor to the crown and President of the [[Oberlandesgericht]] in [[K\u00f6nigsberg]], and Sophie von M\u00fchler (1816\u20131877), who was the daughter of the Prussian Justice minister Heinrich Gottlob von M\u00fchler (1780\u20131857). This marriage produced four children: the Prussian Minister of State and Oberpr\u00e4sident of the province of [[West Prussia]], Gustav (1838\u20131902), the Prussian Minister of War and General of the Infantry, Heinrich (1841\u20131927), the Prussian General of the Infantry, Konrad (1848\u20131933), and the Prussian Lieutenant General, Wilhelm von Go\u00dfler (1850\u20131928).\n\nOn 31 August 1872, Gossler married Emma von Sperber (born 14 November 1848; died 3 October 1914), the daughter of the landowner Eugen von Sperber, and of Emilie Donalitius.\n\n==Military career==\nGo\u00dfler joined the 1st Infantry Regiment in 1860, became a [[Second Lieutenant]] in 1861 and took part in the [[Austro-Prussian War]] in 1866.\n\nHe also fought in the [[Franco-Prussian War]] in 1870\u20131871, with distinction. After the war, he was assigned to the Ministry of War as a [[Captain (land)|Captain]] until 1875. He then commanded a company in the 2nd Grenadier Regiment until 1878, when he was once again moved to the War Ministry, to the Department for Army Affairs. Here he was later made a member of the higher examination commission. In 1885 Go\u00dfler became a department head in the War Ministry.\n\nAfter being appointed a colonel in 1888, commander of the 3rd Guard Regiment in 1889 and a Major General and brigade commander in 1891, he was made Director of the General War Department in the War Ministry in October 1891 and simultaneously, representing the War Minister, a member of the Defence Commission. He was also the deputy plenipotentiary in the Bundesrat, chairman of the ''Reichsrayonkommission'' and a member of a disciplinary commission.\n\nGo\u00dfler was a Lieutenant General after 1895 and commanded the 25th Division in [[Darmstadt]]. On 14 August 1896 he was appointed Prussian Minister of War, and in September was also made the Prussian plenipotentiary in the Bundesrat. On 15 August 1903 he retired, having been made a General of the Infantry in 1899.\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Walther Bronsart von Schellendorff]] | title=[[Prussian Minister of War]] | after=[[Karl von Einem]] | years=14 August 1896 &ndash; 15 August 1903}}\u00a7\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prussian Ministers of War}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gossler, Heinrich von}}\n[[Category:1841 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:German untitled nobility]]\n[[Category:Generals of Infantry (Prussia)]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Crown (W\u00fcrttemberg)]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Friedrich Order]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n[[File:Heinrich von Go\u00dfler.JPG|thumb|Heinrich von Go\u00dfler]]\n'''Heinrich Wilhelm Martin von Go\u00dfler''' (29 September 1841, in [[Wei\u00dfenfels]], [[Province of Saxony]] &ndash; 10 January 1927, in [[Wilmersdorf|Berlin-Wilmersdorf]]) was a [[Prussia]]n [[General of the Infantry]] and [[Prussian Minister of War|Minister of War]]. He was a Knight of Justice (''Rechtsritter'') of the [[Order of Saint John (Bailiwick of Brandenburg)|Order of Saint John]].\n\n==Family==\nHe was descended from a family that probably originated from [[Lipov\u00e1 (Cheb District)|Gosel]] in the [[Egerland]] and emigrated to G\u00fcrth (now in [[Bad Brambach]]) before 1630. He was the son of Karl Gustav von Go\u00dfler (1810\u20131885), the ''Kanzler'' (in this case, provincial justice minister) of the province [[East Prussia]], legal advisor to the crown and President of the [[Oberlandesgericht]] in [[K\u00f6nigsberg]], and Sophie von M\u00fchler (1816\u20131877), who was the daughter of the Prussian Justice minister Heinrich Gottlob von M\u00fchler (1780\u20131857). This marriage produced four children: the Prussian Minister of State and Oberpr\u00e4sident of the province of [[West Prussia]], Gustav (1838\u20131902), the Prussian Minister of War and General of the Infantry, Heinrich (1841\u20131927), the Prussian General of the Infantry, Konrad (1848\u20131933), and the Prussian Lieutenant General, Wilhelm von Go\u00dfler (1850\u20131928).\n\nOn 31 August 1872, Gossler married Emma von Sperber (born 14 November 1848; died 3 October 1914), the daughter of the landowner Eugen von Sperber, and of Emilie Donalitius.\n\n==Military career==\nGo\u00dfler joined the 1st Infantry Regiment in 1860, became a [[Second Lieutenant]] in 1861 and took part in the [[Austro-Prussian War]] in 1866.\n\nHe also fought in the [[Franco-Prussian War]] in 1870-1871, with distinction. After the war, he was assigned to the Ministry of War as a [[Captain (land)|Captain]] until 1875. He then commanded a company in the 2nd Grenadier Regiment until 1878, when he was once again moved to the War Ministry, to the Department for Army Affairs. Here he was later made a member of the higher examination commission. In 1885 Go\u00dfler became a department head in the War Ministry.\n\nAfter being appointed a colonel in 1888, commander of the 3rd Guard Regiment in 1889 and a Major General and brigade commander in 1891, he was made Director of the General War Department in the War Ministry in October 1891 and simultaneously, representing the War Minister, a member of the Defence Commission. He was also the deputy plenipotentiary in the Bundesrat, chairman of the ''Reichsrayonkommission'' and a member of a disciplinary commission.\n\nGo\u00dfler was a Lieutenant General after 1895 and commanded the 25th Division in [[Darmstadt]]. On 14 August 1896 he was appointed Prussian Minister of War, and in September was also made the Prussian plenipotentiary in the Bundesrat. On 15 August 1903 he retired, having been made a General of the Infantry in 1899.\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Walther Bronsart von Schellendorff]] | title=[[Prussian Minister of War]] | after=[[Karl von Einem]] | years=14 August 1896 &ndash; 15 August 1903}}\u00a7\n\n{{Prussian Ministers of War}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gossler, Heinrich von}}\n[[Category:1841 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:German untitled nobility]]\n[[Category:Generals of Infantry (Prussia)]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Crown (W\u00fcrttemberg)]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Friedrich Order]]\n", "name_user": "Anomalocaris", "label": "safe", "comment": "{{s-end}}; dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heinrich_von_Gossler"}
{"title_page": "What Is Love", "text_new": "{{short description|1993 single by Haddaway}}\n{{about|the Haddaway song|other songs of this name and all other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = What Is Love\n| cover      = HaddawayWhatIsLoveMaxiCDCover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Haddaway]]\n| album      = [[The Album (Haddaway album)|The Album]]\n| B-side     = Sing About Love\n| released   = {{unbulleted list|8 May 1993 {{small|(Europe)}}|August 1993 {{small|(US)}}}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[7\" single]]|[[12-inch single|12\" single]]|[[CD single]]|[[cassette single]]}}\n| recorded   = \n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Eurodance]]<ref>{{cite news|first= Leif |last= Raberg |title= First Full dress rehearsals in Gothenburg are over |date= 9 February 2008 |url= http://esctoday.com/10451/first_full_dress_rehearsals_in_gothenburg_are_over/ |publisher= Esctoday.com |accessdate= 1 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Recovery\">{{cite news|first= Jeff |last= Weiss |date= 22 June 2010 |title= Review: 2 1/2 stars for Eminem's 'Recovery' |newspaper= [[Chicago Tribune]] |url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-06-22/entertainment/chi-100622-eminem-recovery-review_1_marshall-mathers-stars-jim-jonsin |quote= Haddaway's \"What Is Love,\" the Eurodance ballad mocked in the \"Saturday Night Live\" skits and spinoff movie. |accessdate= 1 June 2014}}</ref>\n| length     = 4:29\n| label      = [[Coconut Records|Coconut]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Tony Hendrik|Dee Dee Halligan]]|{{nowrap|Junior Torello}}}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Dee Dee Halligan|{{nowrap|Junior Torello}}}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Life (Haddaway song)|Life]]\n| next_year  = 1993\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|HEXWRTEbj1I|\"What Is Love\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''What Is Love'''\" is a song recorded by Trinidadian-German [[Eurodance]] artist [[Haddaway]] for his debut album, ''[[The Album (Haddaway album)|The Album]]''. The song was released on 8 May 1993 as the album's lead single. It was a massive hit in Europe, becoming a number-one hit in at least 13 countries and reaching number two in Germany, Sweden, and the United Kingdom. Outside Europe, the song was moderately successful, reaching number 11 in the United States, number 12 in Australia, number 17 in Canada, and number 48 in New Zealand.\n\n==Background==\n\"What Is Love\" was written and produced by German music producer and composer Dee Dee Halligan (Dieter L\u00fcnstedt a.k.a. [[Tony Hendrik]]) and Junior Torello (Karin Hartmann-Eisenbl\u00e4tter a.k.a. Karin van Haaren) of [[Coconut Records]] near [[Cologne]]. They were waiting for the right singer for the song. [[Trinidadians and Tobagonians|Trinidadian-born]] singer Nestor Alexander Haddaway was then chosen to sing it. He used to work as a producer, dancer and choreographer before he was signed to [[Coconut Records]].<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Robbert |last= Tilli |title= Haddaway Makes Headway Into Europe |magazine= [[Music & Media]] |volume= 10 |issue= 18 |page= 14 |date= 1 May 1993 |accessdate= 7 March 2020 |url= http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1993/MM-1993-05-01.pdf}}</ref> In a 2012 interview Haddaway said about the making of \"What Is Love\":\n\n{{cquote|We just used ideas that were fresh at that time and tried to make something that nobody else had, (...) The song came really fast. I had the idea for the melodies in about 45 minutes and the total structure of the song was done in a day and a half.<ref>{{cite news|first= Saeed |last= Saeed |title= Take a trip down memory lane at the Mixtape Rewind festival |newspaper= [[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |date= 13 November 2012 |accessdate= 14 February 2018 |url= https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/music/take-a-trip-down-memory-lane-at-the-mixtape-rewind-festival-1.370608}}</ref>}}\n\n==Release and legacy==\n\"What Is Love\" was released in Europe in May 1993 and in the US in August 1993. It peaked at number two in the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Germany]] and hit number one in 13 other countries: Austria, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, France, Ireland, Italy, Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain, Switzerland and Zimbabwe. Debuting at number 87 on 28 August 1993, the song reached number 11 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] in the [[United States]]. The song also peaked at number\n# \n*  12 in [[Australia]]. By March 1994, worldwide sales of \"What Is Love\" had already reached 2.6 million.<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Ellie |last= Weinert |title= Casebook: Haddaway |url= https://books.google.com/?id=NQgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA58&dq=%22million+copies%22 |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= 26 March 1994 |volume= 106 |issue= 13 |page= 58 |issn= 0006-2510}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked about the meaning of \"What Is Love\" in a 2015 interview, Haddaway said:\n\n{{cquote|People always ask me about what I meant, (...) I meant that 'what is love' needs to be defined by everyone by his own definition. It's unique and individual. For me, it has to do with trust, honesty, and dedication.<ref>{{cite web|first= Jillian |last= Mapes |title= We Asked Haddaway, \"What Is Love?\" Here's What He Said |website= [[Flavorwire]] |date= 12 February 2015 |accessdate= 14 February 2018 |url= http://flavorwire.com/504266/we-asked-haddaway-what-is-love-heres-what-he-said}}</ref>}}\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[AllMusic]] editor Jose F. Promis called the song \"one of the 1990s' quintessential dance tunes\".<ref>{{cite web|first= Jose F. |last= Promis |title= Haddaway \u2013 The Album: 2nd Edition |website= [[AllMusic]] |accessdate= 15 February 2020 |url= https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-album-2nd-edition-mw0000922934}}</ref> Victor Beigelman from [[The A.V. Club]] noted it as a \"Europop banger that more than 20 years later remains relentlessly catchy and far more profound than it ever had any right to be.\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Victor |last= Beigelman |title= Haddaway\u2019s \u201cWhat Is Love\u201d is the one-hit wonder that keeps hitting home |work= [[The A.V. Club]] |date= 28 December 2015 |accessdate= 20 April 2020 |url= https://music.avclub.com/haddaway-s-what-is-love-is-the-one-hit-wonder-that-ke-1798287608}}</ref> [[Larry Flick]] from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' described it as a \"glorious pop/house ditty\" and noted that \"wildly catchy chorus is complemented by a slick, synth-happy arrangement. Haddaway will conjure up images of [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] and [[Sydney Youngblood]] with his worldly baritone delivery. A sure-fire dance hit that has the muscle to push its way onto pop formats with ease.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Larry |last= Flick |title= Single Reviews > New & Noteworthy |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= 31 October 1992 |page= 84 |url= http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1993/BB-1993-06-26.pdf}}</ref> ''[[Columbia Daily Spectator]]'' wrote that the song \"will transport you instantly to the golden age of house music.\"<ref>{{cite newspaper|first1= Atossa |last1= Abrahamian |first2= John |last2= Klopfer |title= From Dashboard to Dixie Chicks, Pop is More Than Just Pep |newspaper= [[Columbia Daily Spectator]] |page= B5 |date= 21 October 2005 |accessdate= 15 March 2020 |url= http://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/cgi-bin/columbia?a=d&d=cs20051021-02.2.17}}</ref> Dave Sholin from the ''[[Gavin Report]]'' commented, \"Try sitting still seconds after this upbeat entry kicks in.\" He also noted that Haddaway's style is \"reminscent of the [[Fine Young Cannibals]] and just as exciting.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Dave |last= Sholin |title= Gavin Picks > Singles |magazine= [[Gavin Report]] |issue= 1967 |page= 50 |date= 13 August 1993 |accessdate= 15 April 2018 |url= http://americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Gavin-Report/90/93/Gavin-1993-08-13.pdf}}</ref> Mike Wood from ''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'' called it a \"catchy\" anthem that \"permeated our collective consciousness given the heavily-repeated airplay\".<ref>{{cite web|first= Mike |last= Wood |title= The 50 Best Pop Singles of 1994 (Featuring New Interviews with Ace of Base, TLC, Lisa Loeb, Real McCoy & Haddaway) |website= [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |date= 20 November 2014 |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |url= https://www.idolator.com/7569924/50-best-pop-singles-1994-interview-ace-of-base-tlc-lisa-loeb-real-mccoy-haddaway}}</ref> ''[[Music & Media]]'' said that the song has a \"fast house beat augmented by Nestor Haddaway's deeply soulful vocals. This is definitely on par with anything that has come out of Chicago's deep house scene for quite some time.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title= New Releases > Singles |magazine= [[Music & Media]] |volume= 10 |issue= 9 |page= 13 |date= 27 February 1993 |accessdate= 27 April 2019 |url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1993/MM-1993-02-27.pdf}}</ref> Wendi Cermak from ''The Network Forty'' described it as \"splendiferous\" and noted that \"the eargasmic synth stabs in the extended mix are pulling even odds in Vegas for Dance-floor-filling capability and the edit screams for radio airplay...\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Music Meeting |magazine= The Network Forty |page= 30 |date= 28 May 1993 |accessdate= 22 March 2020 |url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Network-40/93/Network-40-1993-05-28.pdf}}</ref> Luke Turner from [[The Quietus]] wrote that \"What Is Love\" \"bangs because it manages to be two things - a terrific soul tune but also rather stern as well, with infernally naggy synth lines and drilled repetition in the rhythms.\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Luke |last= Turner |title= Absolved! The Quietus Writers' 50 Favourite Guilt-Free Pleasures |work= [[The Quietus]] |date= 4 August 2014 |accessdate= 20 April 2020 |url= https://thequietus.com/articles/15896-guilt-free-pleasures-songs-list}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video of \"What Is Love\" was directed by German music video director Volker Hannwacker.<ref>{{cite web|title= What Is Love (1993) by Haddaway |website= IMVD.com |accessdate= 31 January 2017 |url= https://imvdb.com/video/haddaway/what-is-love}}</ref> It features Haddaway performing in an old castle, surrounded by vampire-like dominatrices.\n\n==Accolades==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Publisher\n!Country\n!Accolade\n!Rank\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|\"Awesome One-Hit Wonders of the 1990s\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first= John |last= Barrett |title= 25 Awesome One-Hit Wonders of the 1990s |magazine= [[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date= 28 September 2011 |accessdate= 7 October 2018 |url= https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/09/25-awesome-one-hit-wonders-of-the-1990s.html}}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n|2011\n|[[MTV Dance]]\n|[[United Kingdom]]\n|\"The 100 Biggest 90's Dance Anthems of All Time\"<ref>MTV Dance Tuesday 27.12.2011</ref>\n|57\n|-\n|2012\n|''Porcys''\n|[[Poland]]\n|\"100 Singli 1990-1999\"<ref>{{cite web|title= 100 Singli 1990-1999 |website= Porcys |date= 20 August 2012 |accessdate= 31 October 2019 |url= http://www.porcys.com/ranking/100-singli-1990-1999/3/ |language= pl}}</ref>\n|77\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''\n|United States\n|\"10 Essential Eurodance Classics\"<ref>{{cite magazine|author= 808sJAKE |title= 10 Essential Eurodance Classics |magazine= [[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date= 5 July 2013 |accessdate= 8 October 2018 |url= https://www.complex.com/music/2013/07/10-essential-eurodance-classics/haddaway-what-is-love-2}}</ref>\n|*\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]''\n|United States\n|\"Before EDM: 30 Dance Tracks from the '90s That Changed the Game\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Before EDM: 30 Dance Tracks from the '90s That Changed the Game |magazine= [[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |date= 22 July 2013 |accessdate= 8 October 2018 |url= https://www.vibe.com/2013/07/edm-30-dance-tracks-90s-changed-game/corona/}}</ref> \n|4\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]''\n|United States\n|\"The 50 Best Pop Singles of 1994\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Robbie |last= Daw |title= The 50 Best Pop Singles of 1994 (Featuring New Interviews with Ace of Base, TLC, Lisa Loeb, Real McCoy & Haddaway) |website= [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |date= 20 November 2014 |accessdate= 5 October 2018 |url= https://www.idolator.com/7569924/50-best-pop-singles-1994-interview-ace-of-base-tlc-lisa-loeb-real-mccoy-haddaway/6}}</ref>\n|5\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[BuzzFeed]]''\n|United States\n|\"The 101 Greatest Dance Songs of the '90s\"<ref>{{cite web|first1= Matt |last1= Stopera |first2= Brian |last2= Galindo |title= The 101 Greatest Dance Songs of the '90s |website= [[BuzzFeed]] |date= 11 March 2017 |accessdate= 5 October 2018 |url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/mjs538/jump-to-the-rhythm-jump-jump-to-the-rhythm-jump}}</ref>\n|11\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''\n|United States\n|\"52 Best 1990s Pop Songs\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Estelle |last= Tang |title= 52 Best 1990s Pop Songs |magazine= [[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |date= 1 August 2019 |accessdate= 15 September 2019 |url= https://www.elle.com/culture/music/g28505129/best-90s-pop-songs/}}</ref>\n|39\n|-\n|2019\n|''Insider''\n|United States\n|\"The 57 best one-hit wonders of all time\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Gabbi |last= Shaw |title= The 57 best one-hit wonders of all time |website= Insider |date= 25 September 2019 |accessdate= 16 December 2019 |url= https://www.insider.com/best-one-hit-wonders-2018-5}}</ref>\n|*\n|-\n|}\n<small>(*) indicates the list is unordered.</small>\n\n==In popular culture==\n\"What is Love\" experienced a revival as the song from the ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' \"[[Roxbury Guys]]\" sketches later expanded into the 1998 feature film ''[[A Night at the Roxbury]]'', where two brothers (played by [[Chris Kattan]] and [[Will Ferrell]]) frequently went to dance clubs with a third person (including actors such as [[Sylvester Stallone]] and [[Jim Carrey]]), credited as \"Barhop\". It was also used in the 2013 video game ''[[Saints Row IV]]'' and included as one of the tracks in ''[[Just Dance 2017]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first= Jenna |last= Pitcher |title= Saints Row 4 tracklist revealed, features 109 tracks |website= [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date= 6 August 2013 |accessdate= 4 July 2016 |url= http://www.polygon.com/2013/8/6/4593292/saints-row-4-track-list-revealed}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first= Eddie |last= Makuch |title= Just Dance 2017 Song List Revealed |date= 14 October 2016 |website= [[GameSpot]] |accessdate= 21 January 2018 |url= https://www.gamespot.com/articles/just-dance-2017-song-list-revealed/1100-6444469/}}</ref> The song was also sung by [[Ulysses Klaue]] (played by [[Andy Serkis]]) while being interrogated by [[Everett K. Ross]] (played by [[Martin Freeman]]) in the 2018 film ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8100172/black-panther-movie-best-music-moments|title='Black Panther' Movie: 5 Best Music Moments|date=2018-02-16|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Formats and track listings==\n; \"What Is Love\"\n;; CD single / 7\"\n# \"What Is Love\" \u2013 4:28\n# \"Sing About Love\" \u2013 3:12\n\n;; CD single \u2013 United Kingdom\n#\"What Is Love\" Radio Edit 7\" Mix \u2013 3:57\n#\"What Is Love\" Club Mix \u2013 5:00\n#\"What Is Love\" 12\" Mix \u2013 6:40\n#\"What Is Love\" Tour De Trance Mix \u2013 6:00\n#\"What Is Love\" Refreshmento Extro Mix \u2013 5:42\n\n;; CD maxi \u2013 France\n#\"What Is Love\" (7\" mix) \u2013 4:29\n#\"What Is Love\" (12\" mix) \u2013 6:40\n#\"What Is Love\" (club mix) \u2013 5:02\n#\"Sing About Love\" \u2013 4:36\n\n; \"What Is Love\" \u2013 remix\n;; CD single \u2013 France\n#\"What Is Love\" (eat-this mix \u2013 radio edit) \u2013 4:19\n#\"What Is Love\" (refreshmento extro mix) \u2013 3:52\n\n;; CD maxi\n#\"What Is Love\" \u2013 remix (eat-this mix) \u2013 6:54\n#\"What