ales Charts |magazine= [[Music & Media]] |volume= 10 |issue= 51/52 |page= 15 |date= 18 December 1993 |accessdate= 18 November 2019 |url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1993/MM-1993-12-18.pdf}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n|Germany ([[GfK Entertainment|Media Control Charts]])<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.officialcharts.de/year.asp?cat=s&country=de&year=1993&x=39&y=5 |title= Jahrescharts \u2013 1993 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140714201900/http://www.officialcharts.de/year.asp?cat=s&country=de&year=1993&x=39&y=5 |archivedate= 14 July 2014|language=de}}. Officialcharts.de. [[GfK Entertainment]].</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n|Italy ([[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web|title= I singoli pi\u00f9 venduti del 1993 |publisher= Hit Parade Italia. [[Creative Commons]] |url= http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/hp_yends/hpe1993.htm |accessdate= 23 January 2014 |language= it}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Dutch Top 40]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 1993 |publisher= [[Dutch Top 40]] |accessdate= 23 January 2014 |url= http://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/1993 |language= nl}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Single Top 100]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1993 |publisher= [[Single Top 100]]. Hung Medien |accessdate= 23 January 2014 |url= http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1993&cat=s |language= nl}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n|Switzerland ([[Swiss Hitparade|Schweizer Hitparade]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Schweizer Jahreshitparade 1993 |publisher= Hitparade.ch. Hung Medien |url= http://hitparade.ch/year.asp?key=1993 |accessdate= 23 January 2014 |language= de}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n|UK Singles ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite book|first= Neil |last= Warwick |first2= Jon |last2= Kutner |first3= Tony |last3= Brown |title= The Complete Book of the British Charts: Singles and Albums |publisher= [[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]] |year= 2004 |edition= 3rd |isbn= 978-1-8444-9058-5 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1993 |title= Top 100 Hits for 1993 |website= The Longbored Surfer |accessdate= 23 January 2014}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|82\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1994)\n!Position\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web |title= Top 100 Hits for 1994 |publisher= The Longbored Surfer |accessdate= 23 January 2014 |url= http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1994.php |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140101130345/http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1994.php |archivedate= 1 January 2014 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|97\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Certifications and sales===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|type=single|artist=Haddaway|title=What Is Love|award=Gold|relyear=1993|certyear=1994|certref=<ref name=\"ryan\"/>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Austria|type=single|artist=Haddaway|title=What Is Love|award=Platinum|relyear=1993|certyear=1993}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Denmark|type=single|artist=Haddaway|title=What Is Love|award=Gold|relyear=1993|certyear=2017}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Germany|type=single|artist=Haddaway|title=What Is Love|award=Gold|number=3|relyear=1993|certyear=1993}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Sweden|type=single|artist=Haddaway|title=What Is Love|award=Gold|relyear=1993|certyear=1993}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=Haddaway|title=What Is Love|award=Gold|relyear=1993|certyear=1993}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=single|artist=Haddaway|title=What Is Love|award=Gold|relyear=1993|certyear=1994}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Cover versions and sampling==\n*In 2007, the song was covered by indie band [[Gossip (band)|The Gossip]], with lead singer [[Beth Ditto]] changing the lyrics to \"When Is Lunch?, Baby I'm Hungry, I'm Hungry, For More\".<ref>{{cite news|first= Simon |last= Price |title= Interpol/The Gossip, Reading Festival |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 2 September 2007 |accessdate= 23 January 2014 |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/interpolthe-gossip-reading-festival-463808.html}}</ref>\n*In 2009, singer and songwriter [[Diane Birch]] completely rearranged the song,<ref>{{cite web|title= Diane Birch In Concert |publisher= [[NPR]] |url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=105783310 |date= 26 June 2009 |accessdate= 24 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Diane Birch covers Haddaway's \"What Is Love?\" |url= http://loft965.com/2009/07/27/diane-birch-covers-haddaways-what-is-love/ |website= Loft965.com |date= 27 July 2009 |accessdate= 23 January 2014}}</ref> that later was featured on ''Billboard'' magazine's Mashup Monday in 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Diane Birch De-Clubs \"What Is Love\" |magazine= Billboard |url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/mashup-mondays/959122/diane-birch-de-clubs-what-is-love |date= 8 March 2010 |accessdate= 23 January 2014}}</ref>\n*In 2010, [[Sharaya J]] sampled the chorus for her performance on [[Missy Elliott]]'s European tour.<ref>{{cite web|title= Sharaya @ Bamboo Mamaia \u2013 16 iulie 2010 \u2013 HD video 5a |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8Bd2b6w3lpA |publisher= [[YouTube]] |date= 16 July 2010 |accessdate= 15 March 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2010, Swedish [[boy band]] [[E.M.D.]] released a piano ballad version of \"What Is Love\" as the second single from their sophomore [[studio album]] ''[[Rewind (E.M.D. album)|Rewind]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title= EMD cover Haddaway's 'What Is Love'! |publisher= Scandipop |date= 28 October 2010 |url= http://www.scandipop.co.uk/emd-cover-haddaways-what-is-love/ |accessdate= 23 January 2014}}</ref>\n*In 2010, American rappers [[Eminem]] and [[Lil Wayne]] sampled the song for the single \"[[No Love]]\" from Eminem's seventh studio album, ''[[Recovery (Eminem album)|Recovery]]''.<ref name=\"Recovery\"/>\n*In 2013, it was covered by the band Foolstop in a rock style.<ref>{{cite web|title= Foolstop \u2013 What Is Love (Haddaway Rock Cover) |publisher= YouTube |date= 30 April 2013 |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LFWw-9fmlmQ |accessdate= 23 January 2014}}</ref>\n*In 2014, Canadian singer [[Kiesza]] did a \"piano-and-synth cover\" of the song.<ref>{{cite web|first= Robbie |last= Daw |title= Kiesza Covers Haddaway's \"What Is Love\": Watch The Video For Her Rendition Of The '90s Classic |url= http://www.idolator.com/7515322/kiesza-cover-haddaway-what-is-love-listen |publisher= [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |accessdate= 1 May 2014 |date= 23 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Klaas version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Klaas meets Haddaway \u2013 What Is Love 2K9\n| cover      = What-Is-Love-2k9.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Klaas (DJ)|Klaas]]\n| album      =\n| released   = 2009\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     =\n| label      = Mostiko\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Tony Hendrik|Dee Dee Halligan]]|Junior Torello}}\n| producer   = [[Klaas (DJ)|Klaas]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|-YZ9V9-WWgE|\"What is Love 2K9\"}}}}\n}}\nIn 2009, German DJ [[Klaas (DJ)|Klaas]] remixed the song under the title \"Klaas meets Haddaway \u2013 What Is Love 2K9\". This remix charted in several European countries.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2009)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|37|artist=Klaas meets Haddaway|song=What Is Love 2K9|accessdate=23 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|41|artist=Klaas meets Haddaway|song=What Is Love 2K9|accessdate=23 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|9|artist=Klaas meets Haddaway|song=What Is Love 2K9|accessdate=23 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|5|artist=Klaas meets Haddaway|song=What Is Love 2K9|accessdate=23 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|60|songid=593843|artist=Klaas meets Haddaway|song=What Is Love 2K9|accessdate=23 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|49|artist=Klaas meets Haddaway|song=What Is Love 2K9|accessdate=23 January 2014}}\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Lost Frequencies version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = What Is Love 2016\n| cover      = What-Is-Love-2016-Lost-Frequencies.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Lost Frequencies]]\n| album      = [[Less Is More (Lost Frequencies album)|Less Is More]]\n| released   = 7 October 2016\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 2:52\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Armada Music|Armada]]|Mostiko}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Tony Hendrik|Dee Dee Halligan]]|Junior Torello|[[Lost Frequencies|Felix De Laet]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Hal Ritson]]|Felix De Laet}}\n| prev_title = [[Beautiful Life (Lost Frequencies song)|Beautiful Life]]\n| prev_year  = 2016\n| next_title = All or Nothing\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|yXiP7h_BD1Q|\"What Is Love 2016\"}}}}\n}}\nIn 2016, Belgian DJ [[Lost Frequencies]] released a cover titled \"What Is Love 2016\", as a single from his debut album ''[[Less Is More (Lost Frequencies album)|Less Is More]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first= Hans |last= Op de Beeck |title= Wordt ook vierde single Lost Frequencies schot in de roos? \"Als het te slap is, dan is het gewoon te slap\" |newspaper= [[Het Laatste Nieuws]] |date= 7 October 2016 |accessdate= 8 October 2016 |url= http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/9092/Muzieknieuws/article/detail/2905385/2016/10/07/Wordt-ook-vierde-single-Lost-Frequencies-schot-in-de-roos-Als-het-te-slap-is-dan-is-het-gewoon-te-slap.dhtml |language= nl}}</ref> It was actually already produced back in 2014 as a remix for Jaymes Young's cover version of \"What is Love\". This version was remade for the album and became a hit on a number of European singles charts and topped the Belgian [[Ultratop]] Official Singles Chart.\n\n====Music video====\nAn official music video was released directed by Soulvizion. It features the Dutch professional [[basketball]] player [[Don Rigters]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://social.quedeletras.com/lost-frequencies-what-is-love-2016/ |title= Lost Frequencies \u2013 What Is Love 2016 |work= Social M\u00fasica Musica |date= 7 October 2016 |accessdate= 16 November 2016}}</ref> who plays the role of David Rose, a basketball player who is severely injured trying to make a comeback to the game with encouragement from his girlfriend, (played by Melissa Kanza), his three teammates, (Alkenah Wansing, Jeroen Jansen and Lindy Chippendel) and by his basketball coach (played  by J E Rigters).\n\n====Track listing====\n*'''Armada / Mostiko, 7 October 2016'''\n#\"What Is Love 2016\" \u2013 2:52\n\n*'''Armada / Mostiko, 28 October 2016'''\n#What Is Love 2016\" ([[Regi Penxten|Regi]] & Lester Williams Remix) \u2013 4:21\n\n*'''Lost & Cie / Armada, 11 November 2016'''\n#\"What Is Love 2016\" (Regi & Lester Williams Remix) \u2013 3:08\n#\"What Is Love 2016\" (Regi & Lester Williams Extended Remix) \u2013 4:10\n\n*'''Armada / Mostiko, 6 January 2017'''\n#\"What Is Love 2016\" ([[Mike Mago]] Remix) \u2013 3:29\n#\"What Is Love 2016\" ([[Zonderling]] Remix) \u2013 3:11\n#\"What Is Love 2016\" (Galactic Marvl Remix) \u2013 2:54\n#\"What Is Love 2016\" (Rose Remix) \u2013 3:08\n#\"What Is Love 2016\" (Mike Mago Extended Remix) \u2013 5:49\n#\"What Is Love 2016\" (Zonderling Extended Remix) \u2013 4:27\n#\"What Is Love 2016\" (Rose Extended Remix) \u2013 4:08\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2016\u20132017)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|20|artist=Lost Frequencies|song=What Is Love 2016|accessdate=1 December 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|1|artist=Lost Frequencies|song=What Is Love 2016|accessdate=23 November 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|12|artist=Lost Frequencies|song=What Is Love 2016|accessdate=3 December 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|92|artist=Lost Frequencies|song=What Is Love 2016|accessdate=23 November 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|24|songid=1597408|artist=Lost Frequencies|song=What Is Love 2016|accessdate=23 November 2016}}\n|-\n|Germany ([[German Airplay Chart|Airplay Chart]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Airplay Charts Deutschland \u2013 Woche 51/2016 |publisher= German Charts |accessdate= 30 January 2017 |url= http://germancharts.com/airplay_charts.asp?week=201651 |language= de}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n{{singlechart|Hungary|40|year=2016|week=48|artist=Lost Frequencies|song=What Is Love 2016|accessdate=10 December 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|73|artist=Lost Frequencies|song=What Is Love 2016|accessdate=10 December 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Poland|29|chartid=2217|year=2017|accessdate=6 February 2017|refname=Poland2}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Slovakia|38|year=2016|week=50|accessdate=20 December 2016}}\n|-\n|Slovenia ([[SloTop50]])<ref>{{cite web|title= SloTop50 \u2013 Tedenska lestvica : 4 Teden 23.01.2017 \u2013 29.01.2017 |website= SloTop50 |accessdate= 29 August 2018 |url= https://www.slotop50.si/Glasbene-lestvice/Tedenske-lestvice/?year=2017&week=4}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|20 \n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|99|artist=Lost Frequencies|song=What Is Love 2016|accessdate=23 November 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|52|artist=Lost Frequencies|song=What Is Love 2016|accessdate=23 November 2016}}\n|}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (2016)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Belgium ([[Ultratop|Ultratop 50]] Flanders)<ref>{{cite web|title= Jaaroverzichten 2016 |publisher= [[Ultratop]]. Hung Medien |accessdate= 29 December 2016 |url= http://www.ultratop.be/nl/annual.asp?year=2016 |language= nl}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|41\n|}\n\n====Certifications====\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Belgium|type=single|artist=Lost Frequencies|title=What Is Love 2016|award=Platinum|number=2|relyear=2016|certyear=2019|accessdate=1 October 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Germany|type=single|artist=Lost Frequencies|title=What Is Love 2016|award=Gold|relyear=2016|certyear=2017|accessdate=8 September 2017}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Dutch Top 40 number-one singles of 1993]]\n*[[List of number-one hits of 1993 (Austria)]]\n*[[List of number-one hits of 1993 (Italy)]]\n*[[List of number-one singles of 1993 (Finland)]]\n*[[List of number-one singles of 1993 (France)]]\n*[[List of number-one singles of 1993 (Spain)]]\n*[[List of number-one singles of the 1990s (Switzerland)#1993|List of number-one singles of the 1990s (Switzerland)]]\n*[[VG-lista 1964 to 1994]]\n*[[VRT Top 30 number-one hits of 1993]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs release|149375|What Is Love|type=single}}\n*{{MetroLyrics song|haddaway|what-is-love}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Haddaway}}\n{{Lost Frequencies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:What Is Love (Song)}}\n[[Category:1993 debut singles]]\n[[Category:1993 songs]]\n[[Category:2009 singles]]\n[[Category:2016 singles]]\n[[Category:Dutch Top 40 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Single Top 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:European Hot 100 Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Haddaway songs]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Kiesza songs]]\n[[Category:Lost Frequencies songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Austria]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Finland]]\n[[Category:SNEP Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Italy]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Spain]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Dee Dee Halligan]]\n[[Category:Ultratop 50 Singles (Flanders) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Volker Hannwacker]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1993 single by Haddaway}}\n{{about|the Haddaway song|other songs of this name and all other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = What Is Love\n| cover      = HaddawayWhatIsLoveMaxiCDCover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Haddaway]]\n| album      = [[The Album (Haddaway album)|The Album]]\n| B-side     = Sing About Love\n| released   = {{unbulleted list|8 May 1993 {{small|(Europe)}}|August 1993 {{small|(US)}}}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[7\" single]]|[[12-inch single|12\" single]]|[[CD single]]|[[cassette single]]}}\n| recorded   = \n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Eurodance]]<ref>{{cite news|first= Leif |last= Raberg |title= First Full dress rehearsals in Gothenburg are over |date= 9 February 2008 |url= http://esctoday.com/10451/first_full_dress_rehearsals_in_gothenburg_are_over/ |publisher= Esctoday.com |accessdate= 1 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Recovery\">{{cite news|first= Jeff |last= Weiss |date= 22 June 2010 |title= Review: 2 1/2 stars for Eminem's 'Recovery' |newspaper= [[Chicago Tribune]] |url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-06-22/entertainment/chi-100622-eminem-recovery-review_1_marshall-mathers-stars-jim-jonsin |quote= Haddaway's \"What Is Love,\" the Eurodance ballad mocked in the \"Saturday Night Live\" skits and spinoff movie. |accessdate= 1 June 2014}}</ref>\n| length     = 4:29\n| label      = [[Coconut Records|Coconut]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Tony Hendrik|Dee Dee Halligan]]|{{nowrap|Junior Torello}}}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Dee Dee Halligan|{{nowrap|Junior Torello}}}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Life (Haddaway song)|Life]]\n| next_year  = 1993\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|HEXWRTEbj1I|\"What Is Love\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''What Is Love'''\" is a song recorded by Trinidadian-German [[Eurodance]] artist [[Haddaway]] for his debut album, ''[[The Album (Haddaway album)|The Album]]''. The song was released on 8 May 1993 as the album's lead single. It was a massive hit in Europe, becoming a number-one hit in at least 13 countries and reaching number two in Germany, Sweden, and the United Kingdom. Outside Europe, the song was moderately successful, reaching number 11 in the United States, number 12 in Australia, number 17 in Canada, and number 48 in New Zealand.\n\n==Background==\n\"What Is Love\" was written and produced by German music producer and composer Dee Dee Halligan (Dieter L\u00fcnstedt a.k.a. [[Tony Hendrik]]) and Junior Torello (Karin Hartmann-Eisenbl\u00e4tter a.k.a. Karin van Haaren) of [[Coconut Records]] near [[Cologne]]. They were waiting for the right singer for the song. [[Trinidadians and Tobagonians|Trinidadian-born]] singer Nestor Alexander Haddaway was then chosen to sing it. He used to work as a producer, dancer and choreographer before he was signed to [[Coconut Records]].<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Robbert |last= Tilli |title= Haddaway Makes Headway Into Europe |magazine= [[Music & Media]] |volume= 10 |issue= 18 |page= 14 |date= 1 May 1993 |accessdate= 7 March 2020 |url= http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1993/MM-1993-05-01.pdf}}</ref> In a 2012 interview Haddaway said about the making of \"What Is Love\":\n\n{{cquote|We just used ideas that were fresh at that time and tried to make something that nobody else had, (...) The song came really fast. I had the idea for the melodies in about 45 minutes and the total structure of the song was done in a day and a half.<ref>{{cite news|first= Saeed |last= Saeed |title= Take a trip down memory lane at the Mixtape Rewind festival |newspaper= [[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |date= 13 November 2012 |accessdate= 14 February 2018 |url= https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/music/take-a-trip-down-memory-lane-at-the-mixtape-rewind-festival-1.370608}}</ref>}}\n\n==Release and legacy==\n\"What Is Love\" was released in Europe in May 1993 and in the US in August 1993. It peaked at number two in the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Germany]] and hit number one in 13 other countries: Austria, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, France, Ireland, Italy, Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain, Switzerland and Zimbabwe. Debuting at number 87 on 28 August 1993, the song reached number 11 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] in the [[United States]]. The song also peaked at number 12 in [[Australia]]. By March 1994, worldwide sales of \"What Is Love\" had already reached 2.6 million.<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Ellie |last= Weinert |title= Casebook: Haddaway |url= https://books.google.com/?id=NQgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA58&dq=%22million+copies%22 |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= 26 March 1994 |volume= 106 |issue= 13 |page= 58 |issn= 0006-2510}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked about the meaning of \"What Is Love\" in a 2015 interview, Haddaway said:\n\n{{cquote|People always ask me about what I meant, (...) I meant that 'what is love' needs to be defined by everyone by his own definition. It's unique and individual. For me, it has to do with trust, honesty, and dedication.<ref>{{cite web|first= Jillian |last= Mapes |title= We Asked Haddaway, \"What Is Love?\" Here's What He Said |website= [[Flavorwire]] |date= 12 February 2015 |accessdate= 14 February 2018 |url= http://flavorwire.com/504266/we-asked-haddaway-what-is-love-heres-what-he-said}}</ref>}}\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[AllMusic]] editor Jose F. Promis called the song \"one of the 1990s' quintessential dance tunes\".<ref>{{cite web|first= Jose F. |last= Promis |title= Haddaway \u2013 The Album: 2nd Edition |website= [[AllMusic]] |accessdate= 15 February 2020 |url= https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-album-2nd-edition-mw0000922934}}</ref> Victor Beigelman from [[The A.V. Club]] noted it as a \"Europop banger that more than 20 years later remains relentlessly catchy and far more profound than it ever had any right to be.\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Victor |last= Beigelman |title= Haddaway\u2019s \u201cWhat Is Love\u201d is the one-hit wonder that keeps hitting home |work= [[The A.V. Club]] |date= 28 December 2015 |accessdate= 20 April 2020 |url= https://music.avclub.com/haddaway-s-what-is-love-is-the-one-hit-wonder-that-ke-1798287608}}</ref> [[Larry Flick]] from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' described it as a \"glorious pop/house ditty\" and noted that \"wildly catchy chorus is complemented by a slick, synth-happy arrangement. Haddaway will conjure up images of [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] and [[Sydney Youngblood]] with his worldly baritone delivery. A sure-fire dance hit that has the muscle to push its way onto pop formats with ease.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Larry |last= Flick |title= Single Reviews > New & Noteworthy |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= 31 October 1992 |page= 84 |url= http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1993/BB-1993-06-26.pdf}}</ref> ''[[Columbia Daily Spectator]]'' wrote that the song \"will transport you instantly to the golden age of house music.\"<ref>{{cite newspaper|first1= Atossa |last1= Abrahamian |first2= John |last2= Klopfer |title= From Dashboard to Dixie Chicks, Pop is More Than Just Pep |newspaper= [[Columbia Daily Spectator]] |page= B5 |date= 21 October 2005 |accessdate= 15 March 2020 |url= http://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/cgi-bin/columbia?a=d&d=cs20051021-02.2.17}}</ref> Dave Sholin from the ''[[Gavin Report]]'' commented, \"Try sitting still seconds after this upbeat entry kicks in.\" He also noted that Haddaway's style is \"reminscent of the [[Fine Young Cannibals]] and just as exciting.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Dave |last= Sholin |title= Gavin Picks > Singles |magazine= [[Gavin Report]] |issue= 1967 |page= 50 |date= 13 August 1993 |accessdate= 15 April 2018 |url= http://americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Gavin-Report/90/93/Gavin-1993-08-13.pdf}}</ref> Mike Wood from ''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'' called it a \"catchy\" anthem that \"permeated our collective consciousness given the heavily-repeated airplay\".<ref>{{cite web|first= Mike |last= Wood |title= The 50 Best Pop Singles of 1994 (Featuring New Interviews with Ace of Base, TLC, Lisa Loeb, Real McCoy & Haddaway) |website= [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |date= 20 November 2014 |accessdate= 7 April 2020 |url= https://www.idolator.com/7569924/50-best-pop-singles-1994-interview-ace-of-base-tlc-lisa-loeb-real-mccoy-haddaway}}</ref> ''[[Music & Media]]'' said that the song has a \"fast house beat augmented by Nestor Haddaway's deeply soulful vocals. This is definitely on par with anything that has come out of Chicago's deep house scene for quite some time.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title= New Releases > Singles |magazine= [[Music & Media]] |volume= 10 |issue= 9 |page= 13 |date= 27 February 1993 |accessdate= 27 April 2019 |url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1993/MM-1993-02-27.pdf}}</ref> Wendi Cermak from ''The Network Forty'' described it as \"splendiferous\" and noted that \"the eargasmic synth stabs in the extended mix are pulling even odds in Vegas for Dance-floor-filling capability and the edit screams for radio airplay...\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Music Meeting |magazine= The Network Forty |page= 30 |date= 28 May 1993 |accessdate= 22 March 2020 |url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Network-40/93/Network-40-1993-05-28.pdf}}</ref> Luke Turner from [[The Quietus]] wrote that \"What Is Love\" \"bangs because it manages to be two things - a terrific soul tune but also rather stern as well, with infernally naggy synth lines and drilled repetition in the rhythms.\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Luke |last= Turner |title= Absolved! The Quietus Writers' 50 Favourite Guilt-Free Pleasures |work= [[The Quietus]] |date= 4 August 2014 |accessdate= 20 April 2020 |url= https://thequietus.com/articles/15896-guilt-free-pleasures-songs-list}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video of \"What Is Love\" was directed by German music video director Volker Hannwacker.<ref>{{cite web|title= What Is Love (1993) by Haddaway |website= IMVD.com |accessdate= 31 January 2017 |url= https://imvdb.com/video/haddaway/what-is-love}}</ref> It features Haddaway performing in an old castle, surrounded by vampire-like dominatrices.\n\n==Accolades==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Publisher\n!Country\n!Accolade\n!Rank\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|\"Awesome One-Hit Wonders of the 1990s\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first= John |last= Barrett |title= 25 Awesome One-Hit Wonders of the 1990s |magazine= [[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date= 28 September 2011 |accessdate= 7 October 2018 |url= https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/09/25-awesome-one-hit-wonders-of-the-1990s.html}}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n|2011\n|[[MTV Dance]]\n|[[United Kingdom]]\n|\"The 100 Biggest 90's Dance Anthems of All Time\"<ref>MTV Dance Tuesday 27.12.2011</ref>\n|57\n|-\n|2012\n|''Porcys''\n|[[Poland]]\n|\"100 Singli 1990-1999\"<ref>{{cite web|title= 100 Singli 1990-1999 |website= Porcys |date= 20 August 2012 |accessdate= 31 October 2019 |url= http://www.porcys.com/ranking/100-singli-1990-1999/3/ |language= pl}}</ref>\n|77\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''\n|United States\n|\"10 Essential Eurodance Classics\"<ref>{{cite magazine|author= 808sJAKE |title= 10 Essential Eurodance Classics |magazine= [[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date= 5 July 2013 |accessdate= 8 October 2018 |url= https://www.complex.com/music/2013/07/10-essential-eurodance-classics/haddaway-what-is-love-2}}</ref>\n|*\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]''\n|United States\n|\"Before EDM: 30 Dance Tracks from the '90s That Changed the Game\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Before EDM: 30 Dance Tracks from the '90s That Changed the Game |magazine= [[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |date= 22 July 2013 |accessdate= 8 October 2018 |url= https://www.vibe.com/2013/07/edm-30-dance-tracks-90s-changed-game/corona/}}</ref> \n|4\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]''\n|United States\n|\"The 50 Best Pop Singles of 1994\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Robbie |last= Daw |title= The 50 Best Pop Singles of 1994 (Featuring New Interviews with Ace of Base, TLC, Lisa Loeb, Real McCoy & Haddaway) |website= [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |date= 20 November 2014 |accessdate= 5 October 2018 |url= https://www.idolator.com/7569924/50-best-pop-singles-1994-interview-ace-of-base-tlc-lisa-loeb-real-mccoy-haddaway/6}}</ref>\n|5\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[BuzzFeed]]''\n|United States\n|\"The 101 Greatest Dance Songs of the '90s\"<ref>{{cite web|first1= Matt |last1= Stopera |first2= Brian |last2= Galindo |title= The 101 Greatest Dance Songs of the '90s |website= [[BuzzFeed]] |date= 11 March 2017 |accessdate= 5 October 2018 |url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/mjs538/jump-to-the-rhythm-jump-jump-to-the-rhythm-jump}}</ref>\n|11\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''\n|United States\n|\"52 Best 1990s Pop Songs\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Estelle |last= Tang |title= 52 Best 1990s Pop Songs |magazine= [[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |date= 1 August 2019 |accessdate= 15 September 2019 |url= https://www.elle.com/culture/music/g28505129/best-90s-pop-songs/}}</ref>\n|39\n|-\n|2019\n|''Insider''\n|United States\n|\"The 57 best one-hit wonders of all time\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Gabbi |last= Shaw |title= The 57 best one-hit wonders of all time |website= Insider |date= 25 September 2019 |accessdate= 16 December 2019 |url= https://www.insider.com/best-one-hit-wonders-2018-5}}</ref>\n|*\n|-\n|}\n<small>(*) indicates the list is unordered.</small>\n\n==In popular culture==\n\"What is Love\" experienced a revival as the song from the ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' \"[[Roxbury Guys]]\" sketches later expanded into the 1998 feature film ''[[A Night at the Roxbury]]'', where two brothers (played by [[Chris Kattan]] and [[Will Ferrell]]) frequently went to dance clubs with a third person (including actors such as [[Sylvester Stallone]] and [[Jim Carrey]]), credited as \"Barhop\". It was also used in the 2013 video game ''[[Saints Row IV]]'' and included as one of the tracks in ''[[Just Dance 2017]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first= Jenna |last= Pitcher |title= Saints Row 4 tracklist revealed, features 109 tracks |website= [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date= 6 August 2013 |accessdate= 4 July 2016 |url= http://www.polygon.com/2013/8/6/4593292/saints-row-4-track-list-revealed}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first= Eddie |last= Makuch |title= Just Dance 2017 Song List Revealed |date= 14 October 2016 |website= [[GameSpot]] |accessdate= 21 January 2018 |url= https://www.gamespot.com/articles/just-dance-2017-song-list-revealed/1100-6444469/}}</ref> The song was also sung by [[Ulysses Klaue]] (played by [[Andy Serkis]]) while being interrogated by [[Everett K. Ross]] (played by [[Martin Freeman]]) in the 2018 film ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8100172/black-panther-movie-best-music-moments|title='Black Panther' Movie: 5 Best Music Moments|date=2018-02-16|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Formats and track listings==\n; \"What Is Love\"\n;; CD single / 7\"\n# \"What Is Love\" \u2013 4:28\n# \"Sing About Love\" \u2013 3:12\n\n;; CD single \u2013 United Kingdom\n#\"What Is Love\" Radio Edit 7\" Mix \u2013 3:57\n#\"What Is Love\" Club Mix \u2013 5:00\n#\"What Is Love\" 12\" Mix \u2013 6:40\n#\"What Is Love\" Tour De Trance Mix \u2013 6:00\n#\"What Is Love\" Refreshmento Extro Mix \u2013 5:42\n\n;; CD maxi \u2013 France\n#\"What Is Love\" (7\" mix) \u2013 4:29\n#\"What Is Love\" (12\" mix) \u2013 6:40\n#\"What Is Love\" (club mix) \u2013 5:02\n#\"Sing About Love\" \u2013 4:36\n\n; \"What Is Love\" \u2013 remix\n;; CD single \u2013 France\n#\"What Is Love\" (eat-this mix \u2013 radio edit) \u2013 4:19\n#\"W