{"title_page": "Auburn School District", "text_new": "{{confused|Auburn School (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox school district\n|name                = Auburn School District No. 408 \n|image               = [[File:800px-King County Washington Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Auburn Highlighted.svg.png|275px]]\n|caption             = Map of King County, Washington with incorporated and unincorporated areas of Auburn highlighted\n|motto               = \n|type                = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|school_board        = Ray Vefik, Carol (Helgerson) Seng, Laurie Bishop, Anne Baunach, Lisa Connors\n|superintendent      = Dr. Alan Spiciatti \n|budget              = \n|established         = 1896 \n|teachers            = 762<ref name=\"school\">http://reportcard.ospi.k12.wa.us/summary.aspx?groupLevel=District&schoolId=111&reportLevel=District&orgLinkId=111&yrs=&year=2007-08</ref>\n|grades              = [[pre-kindergarten|Pre-K]] through [[twelfth grade|12]]\n|staff               = 254\n|students            = 14,912<ref name=\"school\"/>\n|conference          = \n|location            = \"James P. Fugate Building\" 915 4th Street NE, Auburn, WA 98002 \n|country             = [[United States]]\n|website             = [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/ Auburn.wednet.edu]\n}}\n'''Auburn School District No. 408''' is a public [[school district]] in [[King County, Washington]], seated in [[Auburn, Washington|Auburn]]. The district encompasses a 62 square-mile area bridging [[King County, Washington]] and [[Pierce County, Washington]], and serves approximately 75,000 residents in [[Auburn, Washington|Auburn]], [[Algona, Washington|Algona]], [[Pacific, Washington|Pacific]], and a small portion of [[Kent, Washington|Kent]], as well as unincorporated [[Census-designated place|census-designated places]] such as [[Lake Morton-Berrydale, Washington|Lake Morton-Berrydale]] and [[Lake Holm, Washington|Lake Holm]].\n\nIn October 2014, the district had an enrollment of 14,900 students. Consisting of 14 elementary schools, 4 middle schools, 3 comprehensive high schools, and 1 alternative high school. \n\nGrowth in the last decade, prompted the district to build a total of 9 new schools (5 [[elementary school]]s, 2 [[middle school]]s, and 2 comprehensive [[high school]]s). While [[Auburn Mountainview High School]] is the newest comprehensive high school built since 1992, Auburn High School (formerly [[Auburn Senior High School]]) will be the newest building added to the Auburn School District in 2014.\nThe district employs 849 certified teachers, and staff, and 801 classified staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auburnareawa.org/education.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813031447/http://www.auburnareawa.org/education.htm |archivedate=2009-08-13 }}</ref> In addition several former students from the district have become well known names, including [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] State governor, [[Christine Gregoire]], [[Dick Scobee|Commander Dick Scobee]], and several other notable names.\n\n==School Board==\n\nThe Auburn School District Board of Directors consists of five members who are elected by the voters of the entire school district. Board members serve four-year staggered terms and must be a registered voter, at the time of their election or appointment, in the [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/cms/lib03/WA01001938/Centricity/Domain/63/RedistrictingMaps_DistrictDirectors.pdf geographical region, known as a Director District], they represent on the board. The board sets school policies within the guidelines of the law and the State Board of Education. Board meetings are held on the second and fourth Monday of month at 7 p.m. at the James P. Fugate Administration Building board room, located at 915 4th St NE, Auburn, WA 98002.<ref>https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=915+4th+Street+Northeast,+Auburn&sll=47.311482,-122.217456&sspn=0.018797,0.05476&ie=UTF8&ll=47.309311,-122.22172&spn=0.009762,0.02738&t=h&z=16&iwloc=A</ref> Special sessions are announced to the public in advance.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ School Board Members<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/Page/68 |title=Auburn School District - School Board Members |publisher=auburn.wednet.edu |date= |accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n!Director!!Director<br>District!!First<br>Elected!!Term<br>End!!Board<br>Position\n|-\n|style=\"width: 200px;\" | Ray Vefik [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&ModuleInstanceID=603&ViewID=7b97f7ed-8e5e-4120-848f-a8b4987d588f&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=188&PageID=68] || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 1 || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 1998 || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 2019 || style=\"width: 160px; text-align: center;\" | President\n|-\n|style=\"width: 200px;\" | Robyn Mulenga [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&ModuleInstanceID=603&ViewID=7b97f7ed-8e5e-4120-848f-a8b4987d588f&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=189&PageID=68] || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 2 || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 2015 || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 2019 || style=\"width: 160px; text-align: center;\" | Vice-President\n|-\n|style=\"width: 200px;\" | Laurie Bishop [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&ModuleInstanceID=603&ViewID=7b97f7ed-8e5e-4120-848f-a8b4987d588f&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=187&PageID=68] || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 3 || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 2013 || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 2021 || style=\"width: 160px; text-align: center;\" | \n|-\n|style=\"width: 200px;\" | Laura Theimer  [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&ModuleInstanceID=603&ViewID=7b97f7ed-8e5e-4120-848f-a8b4987d588f&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=190&PageID=68] || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 4 || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 2018 || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 2019 || style=\"width: 160px; text-align: center;\" | \n|-\n|style=\"width: 200px;\" | Ryan Van Quill [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&ModuleInstanceID=603&ViewID=7b97f7ed-8e5e-4120-848f-a8b4987d588f&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=186&PageID=68] || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 5 || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 2014 || style=\"width: 100px; text-align: center;\" | 2021 || style=\"width: 160px; text-align: center;\" | \n|}\n\n==Schools==\n[[File:Auburn Senior High School Front.jpg|right|150px|Auburn Senior High, opened 1950.]]\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:ARSHentry1.jpg|right|150px|Auburn Riverside High School, opened 1995.]] -->\n[[File:Mountainview overview.jpg|right|150px|Auburn's newest comprehensive High School, Auburn Mountainview. Opened 2006.]]\n\n===High schools===\n:{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!School\n!Location\n!Mascot\n!Colors\n!Approx.<br />Students\n|-\n|[[Auburn High School (Washington)|Auburn High School]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004102219/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/ahs/default.htm]\n|Auburn\n|[[Sports teams named Trojans|Trojans]]\n|Green/Gold\n|align=\"right\"|1,874\n|-\n|[[Auburn Riverside High School]] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20051218101306/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/arhs/])\n|Auburn\n|[[Raven]]s\n|Navy Blue/Teal/Silver\n|align=\"right\"|1,742\n|-\n|[[Auburn Mountainview High School]] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20110716131302/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/amhs/])\n|Auburn\n|[[Lion]]s\n|Blue/Orange\n|align=\"right\"|1,429\n|-\n|[[West Auburn Secondary High School]] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20050524065207/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/wahs/])\n|Auburn\n|[[wolf|Wolves]]\n|Grey\n|align=\"right\"|275\n|}\n\n===Middle schools 6-8===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004104652/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/cascade/default.htm Cascade MS]\n**Cascade Middle School is located in North Auburn, and has a student population of 750. School colors are purple and gold.  Mascot is the Spartans.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004104849/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/mtbaker/default.htm Mt. Baker MS]\n**Mt. Baker Middle School is located in the Southwest Region of Auburn. School colors are burgundy, grey and black.  Mascot is the bulldogs.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004104913/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/olympic/default.htm Olympic MS]\n**Olympic Middle School is located in South Auburn and has about 700 students. School colors are blue and white.  Mascot is the cougars.\n* \n[https://www.auburn.wednet.edu/Domain/12]\n**Rainier Middle School is situated on Lea Hill and has 900 students. School colors are black and red   Mascot is the panthers.\n\n===Elementary schools K-5===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061012095321/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/alpac/default.htm Alpac ES]\n**Located in [[Pacific, Washington]] - Opened in 1973 and named for the cities of Algona and Pacific. Originally an open classroom concept school, but converted to standard classroom ideals in 1983. School colors are red and black. Mascot is the allstars.\n* [http://auburnsd.schoolwires.net/ajes Arthur Jacobsen ES]\n**Opened in 2007, on the former Jacobsen Tree farm and on the lower portion of Auburn Mountainview's campus. School colors are black and gold.  Mascot is the thunderbirds.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004104707/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/chinook/default.htm Chinook ES]\n**Opened in 1963 and named for the nearby White River Fish Hatchery. Located on the Muckleshoot Indian Reservation.School colors are blue and orange. Mascot is the eagles.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004104721/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/dscobee/default.htm Dick Scobee ES]\n**Dick Scobee Elementary opened in 1959 as North Auburn Elementary and was renamed for the famed astronaut and Auburn High School graduate who died as commander of the Space Shuttle Challenger, Dick Scobee. Dick Scobee will be getting a rebuilt school in 2020-2021.  School colors are red, white and blue. Mascot is the challengers. \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004105346/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/eheights/default.htm Evergreen Heights ES]\n**Opened in 1970, located on the West Hill of Auburn. School colors are green, yellow and white. Mascot is the timberwolves.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004105358/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/gildorey/default.htm Gildo Rey ES]\n**Opened in 1969, under the name of South Auburn Elementary and was renamed in 1976 in honor of a longtime faculty member, Gildo Rey. School colors are green and blue.  Mascot is the hawks.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004104733/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/hzlwood/default.htm Hazelwood ES]\n**Opened 1990, on Auburn's Lea Hill. School colors are blue and black. Mascot is the orcas. \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004104330/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/ilalko/default.htm Ilalko ES]\n**Opened 1992. Named after a Native American village, the word \"Ilalko\" means \"Striped Water.\" Located Next to Auburn Riverside.  School colors are teal and black.  Mascot is the huskies.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070630181636/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/lakeland/default.html Lakeland Hills ES]\n**Auburn's largest Elementary school, opened in the Lakeland Hills community 2006. School colors are red and grey. Mascot is the wildcats.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081011182955/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/lakeview Lake View ES]\n**Opened in 1980. School colors are red and black.  Mascot is the cardinals.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004104837/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/leahill/default.htm Lea Hill ES]\n**Opened in 1965 as one of only 11 schools in the United States designated as a National Educational landmark by the National Park Service. School colors are purple and black.  Mascot is the mavericks.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004104926/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/pioneer/default.htm Pioneer ES]\n**Opened in 1950. Home of the Auburn Elites demo team. Pioneer will be housed in Olympic Middle school's old building while the district builds a new Pioneer for 2021-2022 School colors are red, white and blue. Mascot is the patriots.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004105457/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/termpark/default.htm Terminal Park ES]\n**opened in 1945 and it was named for the terminal end of the railroad and the neighborhood where the rail workers lived, Terminal Park.  School colors are blue and yellow.  Mascot is the tigers.  \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004102950/http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/homepages/wash/default.htm Washington ES]\n**The oldest Elementary school in Auburn, located next to Auburn High School, originally opened in 1920, was demolished and re-built in 1970. School colors are red, white and blue. Mascot is the explorers.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/ Auburn School District No. 408]\n* [http://reportcard.ospi.k12.wa.us/?schoolId=111 Auburn School District Report Card]\n\n[[Category:Education in King County, Washington]]\n[[Category:School districts in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Auburn, Washington]]\n", "text_old": "{{confused|Auburn School (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox school district\n|name                = Auburn School District No. 408 \n|image               = [[File:800px-King County Washington Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Auburn Highlighted.svg.png|275px]]\n|caption             = Map of King County, Washington with incorporated and unincorporated areas of Auburn highlighted\n|motto               = \n|type                = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|school_board        = Ray Vefik, Carol (Helgerson) Seng, Laurie Bishop, Anne Baunach, Lisa Connors\n|superintendent      = Dr. Alan Spiciatti \n|budget              = \n|established         = 1896 \n|teachers            = 762<ref name=\"school\">http://reportcard.ospi.k12.wa.us/summary.aspx?groupLevel=District&schoolId=111&reportLevel=District&orgLinkId=111&yrs=&year=2007-08</ref>\n|grades              = [[pre-kindergarten|Pre-K]] through [[twelfth grade|12]]\n|staff               = 254\n|students            = 14,912<ref name=\"school\"/>\n|conference          = \n|location            = \"James P. Fugate Building\" 915 4th Street NE, Auburn, WA 98002 \n|country             = [[United States]]\n|website             = [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/ Auburn.wednet.edu]\n}}\n'''Auburn School District No. 408''' is a public [[school district]] in [[King County, Washington]], seated in [[Auburn, Washington|Auburn]]. The district encompasses a 62 square-mile area bridging [[King County, Washington]] and [[Pierce County, Washington]], and serves approximately 75,000 residents in [[Auburn, Washington|Auburn]], [[Algona, Washington|Algona]], [[Pacific, Washington|Pacific]], and a small portion of [[Kent, Washington|Kent]], as well as unincorporated [[Census-designated place|census-designated places]] such as [[Lake Morton-Berrydale, Washington|Lake Morton-Berrydale]] and [[Lake Holm, Washington|Lake Holm]].\n\nIn October 2014, the district had an enrollment of 14,900 students. Consisting of 14 elementary schools, 4 middle schools, 3 comprehensive high schools, and 1 alternative high school. \n\nGrowth in the last decade, prompted the district to build a total of 9 new schools (5 [[elementary school]]s, 2 [[middle school]]s, and 2 comprehensive [[high school]]s). While [[Auburn Mountainview High School]] is the newest comprehensive high school built since 1992, Auburn High School (formerly [[Auburn Senior High School]]) will be the newest building added to the Auburn School District in 2014.\nThe district employs 849 certified teachers, and staff, and 801 classified staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auburnareawa.org/education.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813031447/http://www.auburnareawa.org/education.htm |archivedate=2009-08-13 }}</ref> In addition several former students from the district have become well known names, including [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] State governor, [[Christine Gregoire]], [[Dick Scobee|Commander Dick Scobee]], and several other notable names.\n\n==School Board==\n\nThe Auburn School District Board of Directors consists of five members who are elected by the voters of the entire school district. Board members serve four-year staggered terms and must be a registered voter, at the time of their election or appointment, in the [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/cms/lib03/WA01001938/Centricity/Domain/63/RedistrictingMaps_DistrictDirectors.pdf geographical region, known as a Director District], they represent on the board. The board sets school policies within the guidelines of the law and the State Board of Education. Board meetings are held on the second and fourth Monday of month at 7 p.m. at the James P. Fugate Administration Building board room, located at 915 4th St NE, Auburn, WA 98002.<ref>https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=915+4th+Street+Northeast,+Auburn&sll=47.311482,-122.217456&sspn=0.018797,0.05476&ie=UTF8&ll=47.309311,-122.22172&spn=0.009762,0.02738&t=h&z=16&iwloc=A</ref> Special sessions are announced to the public in advance.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ School Board Members<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/Page/68 |title=Auburn School District - School Board Members |publisher=auburn.wednet.edu |date= |accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n!Director!!Director<br>District!!First<br>Elected!!Term<br>End!!Board<br>Position\n|-\n|style=\"width: 200px;\" | Ray Vefik [http://www.auburn.wednet.edu/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&ModuleInsta